ether with alternative and Jordan division algebras. Formally, the notion of a quadrangular algebra is derived from the notion of a pseudo-quadratic space (introduced by Jacques Tits in the study of classical groups) over a quaternion division ring. This book contains the complete classification of quadrangular algebras starting from first principles. It also shows how this classification can be made to yield the classification of exceptional Moufang quadrangles as a consequence. The book closes with a chapter on isotopes and the structure group of a quadrangular algebra. Quadrangular Algebras is intended for graduate students of mathematics as well as specialists in buildings, exceptional algebraic groups, and related algebraic structures including Jordan algebras and the algebraic theory of quadratic forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAlgebra. 0aForms, Quadratic. 0aMATHEMATICSvAlgebravGeneral. 0aMATHEMATICSvNumber Theory. 7aMATHEMATICS / Algebra / General.2bisacsh  aAlgebra over a field.  aAlgebraic group.  aAssociative property.  aAxiom.  aClassical group.  aClifford algebra.  aCommutator.  aDefective matrix.  aDivision algebra.  aFiber bundle.  aGeometry.  aIsotropic quadratic form.  aJacques Tits.  aJordan algebra.  aMoufang.  aNon-associative algebra.  aPolygon.  aPrecalculus.  aProjective plane.  aQuadratic form.  aSimple Lie group.  aSubgroup.  aTheorem.  aVector space.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Mathematical Notes eBook-Package 1970-2016z9783110494921oZDB-23-PMN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082694040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400826940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum